--- Summary (Cycle 1, operator-level sweep only) ---

2 genuine case-sensitivity weakenings confirmed and fixed (lines 137, 255),
1 additional site hardened defensively (line 256), all other -match/
-notmatch/-replace/-eq/-ne sites in the file swept and confirmed safe.
Parity with the .sh original re-established and verified end-to-end for
both defect classes (named parameters AND array-splat calling convention
for the status check; named parameters for the --reset scan). All
regression checks (b)-(e) pass with zero failures and match the
coordinator's stated expected counts exactly.

*** CORRECTION (Cycle 2): the above "all other sites safe" conclusion was
INCOMPLETE. The Cycle-1 sweep grepped only PowerShell COMPARISON OPERATORS
(-match/-notmatch/-replace/-eq/-ne/-contains/-like) and missed that several
CMDLETS/language features carry their OWN independent, non-operator
case-(in)sensitivity defaults that a pure operator-grep cannot see. A
gate-cycle-2 evaluator found 2 more genuine sites of this broader class
(Critical + Major). See section 6 below for the full cmdlet-level sweep,
the 2 additional fixes, and their independent parity verification. ***

=== Cycle 2: cmdlet/language-feature-level case-sensitivity sweep ===

--- 6. Sweep methodology (cmdlet/feature level, distinct from Cycle 1's
    operator-level sweep) ---

Cycle 1 only checked comparison OPERATORS. This cycle greps every CMDLET or
language construct known to carry an independent case-sensitivity default
in PowerShell, cross-checked against the .sh original's actual bash/find/
sed/.NET-equivalent semantics:

  grep -n "Select-String" ...
  grep -n "Get-ChildItem" ...              (-Filter/-Include/-Exclude)
  grep -n -- '-like|-notlike' ...
  grep -n -- '-split|\.Split(' ...
  grep -n '\[regex\]::|\[Text.RegularExpressions.Regex\]::' ...
  grep -n "switch " ...                    (-wildcard/-regex switch statements)
  grep -n '\.StartsWith(|\.EndsWith(|\.Contains(|\.IndexOf(|\.Equals(|\.Replace(|\.CompareTo(|\.ToLower(|\.ToUpper(' ...

--- 7. Cycle-2 sweep result list ---

| Site | Feature | Verdict | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| **:135 (pre-fix)** `Select-String -Pattern '^Domain-Model-Status:\s*(.*)$'` | `Select-String` (no `-CaseSensitive`) | **FIXED (Critical)** | `Select-String` is case-insensitive by default; the .sh original's `sed -n 's/^Domain-Model-Status:.../p'` is case-sensitive (no `I` flag) -- confirmed live: a `domain-model-status:`/`DOMAIN-MODEL-STATUS:` field name was INCORRECTLY matched pre-fix -> added **`-CaseSensitive`** |
| **:118 (pre-fix)** `Get-ChildItem -Filter '*.md' -File` | `Get-ChildItem -Filter` | **FIXED (Major)** | `-Filter` on a case-insensitive filesystem (macOS APFS/HFS+ default, the AC-017 CI matrix's `macos-latest` runner) performs case-insensitive glob matching at the .NET/OS layer; the .sh original's bash filename glob (`for p in "$aggregates_dir"/*.md`) is ALWAYS case-sensitive regardless of filesystem, since bash does its own in-memory pattern matching on `readdir()` entries -- confirmed live: a file literally named `card.MD` was INCORRECTLY matched by `-Filter '*.md'` on this macOS dev machine -> replaced with `Get-ChildItem -File \| Where-Object { $_.Name -cmatch '\.md$' }` (evaluator-proposed form) |
| `Get-ChildItem -Directory` (line 255, `--reset` scan) | `Get-ChildItem` with only a TYPE filter (`-Directory`), no name-pattern `-Filter`/`-Include`/`-Exclude` | SAFE | name filtering is done entirely by the already-fixed `-cmatch` in the adjacent `Where-Object`, not by `Get-ChildItem` itself |
| `-like`/`-notlike` | n/a | SAFE | zero occurrences in the file |
| `-split` / `.Split(` | n/a | SAFE | zero occurrences in the file (note for future ports: PowerShell's `-split` operator with a regex pattern is case-INSENSITIVE by default, same class as `-match`; this file simply never uses it) |
| `:145` `[Text.RegularExpressions.Regex]::Replace($content, '(?m)^Domain-Model-Status:[^\r\n]*(\r?)$', ...)` | static `[regex]::Replace()` (no explicit `RegexOptions`) | SAFE | .NET's `Regex` class methods are CASE-SENSITIVE by default when no `RegexOptions.IgnoreCase` is passed -- this is the OPPOSITE default from PowerShell's `-match`/`-replace` OPERATORS, and was confirmed live: a `domain-model-status:` (lowercase) line was correctly left un-normalized by this call while `Domain-Model-Status: Pending` was correctly normalized. No fix needed; this line was already correct by construction (same idiom already used, unfixed, in the sibling `task-review-precheck.ps1`/`impl-review-precheck.ps1` `Get-ReviewedHash` helper) |
| `switch -wildcard`/`switch -regex` | n/a | SAFE | zero `switch` STATEMENTS in the file at all (the only `switch` token is the `[switch]$Reset` parameter type, a grep false-positive already noted in Cycle 1) |
| `:32,:38` `.ToLower()` on SHA-256 hex digest strings | `String.ToLower()` | SAFE | intentional output normalization (hex digest lowercasing), not a security-relevant identity comparison; matches `sha256sum`/`shasum` lowercase-hex convention the .sh original also produces |
| `:86` `$rel.StartsWith($root, [StringComparison]::Ordinal)` | `String.StartsWith` with explicit `StringComparison` | SAFE | already explicitly Ordinal (case-sensitive) |
| `:89` `.Replace('\', '/')` | `String.Replace(string,string)` | SAFE | replacing path-separator characters, which have no case |

No `.Contains(`, `.IndexOf(`, `.Equals(`, `.CompareTo(`, `.EndsWith(` calls exist in the file at all (zero hits).

Conclusion: exactly 2 genuine cmdlet/feature-level case-sensitivity
weakenings (`:135` `Select-String`, `:118` `Get-ChildItem -Filter`),
matching the gate-cycle-2 evaluator's Critical+Major diagnosis exactly. All
other cmdlet/feature-level sites are safe by construction or (for
`[regex]::Replace`) already correct because .NET's static Regex API
defaults to case-sensitive, unlike PowerShell's own operators.

--- 8. Fixes applied (Cycle 2, via Edit tool only) ---

Line 118: `Get-ChildItem -LiteralPath $aggregatesDir -Filter '*.md' -File -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue`
       -> `Get-ChildItem -LiteralPath $aggregatesDir -File -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Where-Object { $_.Name -cmatch '\.md$' }`
Line 135: `Select-String -LiteralPath $contextMap -Pattern '^Domain-Model-Status:\s*(.*)$'`
       -> `Select-String -LiteralPath $contextMap -Pattern '^Domain-Model-Status:\s*(.*)$' -CaseSensitive`

