--- Summary (Cycle 2, supersedes the Cycle-1 summary above) ---

Cycle 1's operator-level sweep found and fixed 2 sites but its "all other
sites safe" conclusion did not extend to cmdlets/language features with
their own independent case-sensitivity defaults (`Select-String`,
`Get-ChildItem -Filter`, `-split`, `[regex]::`, `switch -wildcard/-regex`).
A dedicated Cycle-2 cmdlet-level sweep found exactly 2 more genuine sites
(`:135` `Select-String`, `:118` `Get-ChildItem -Filter`, matching the
gate-cycle-2 evaluator's Critical+Major diagnosis exactly) and confirmed
every other cmdlet/feature site is safe by construction, including one
site (`[regex]::Replace`, `:145`) that is safe precisely BECAUSE .NET's
static Regex API's case-sensitivity default is the OPPOSITE of PowerShell's
own comparison operators. Both new fixes verified end-to-end against the
unedited .sh original (named parameters and array-splat calling
convention), with zero regression across the reject-path pair, all 3
status-value cases, the ROUND-3 reset scan, and both wave-1/hygiene
suites.
